page.text: The Town of Putnam is proposing to develop the Quinebaug Regional Tech Park located on
267± acres along the west side of Kennedy Drive. When completed it is anticipated that the
QRTP will consist of approximately 20 buildings totaling 1,400,000 square feet of light
industrial/ office use and a 48,000 square foot regional YMCA facility. A new access drive is
proposed to intersect Kennedy Drive opposite the existing I‐395 SB Exit Ramp.
Seven intersections in the vicinity of the site were studied to assess the impact of the traffic
that will be generated by the QRTP. These include:
 Park Road at Industrial Park Road
 Park Road at I‐395 NB Ramps
 Kennedy Drive at I‐395 SB Entrance Ramp
 Kennedy Drive at I‐395 SB Exit Ramp
 River Road at Town Farm Road
The traffic impact of the proposed development was determined by calculating the number of
new trips that are expected to be generated by the development. The trip generation volumes
represent the number of trips expected to be added to the roadway during the peak hours of
the proposed development. The anticipated site generated traffic volumes for the QRTP were
calculated using existing empirical data from the Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Trip
Generation, 8th Edition, 2008. Data for Land Uses 130, “Industrial Park” and 495 “Community
Center”. It is anticipated that the traffic impact of the completed QRTP would be 865 vehicle
trips during the weekday morning peak hour and 1190 vehicle trips during the weekday
afternoon peak hour. 693 vehicles will enter and 171 vehicles will exit the development during
the morning peak hour and 261 vehicles will enter and 929 vehicles will exit the facility during
Capacity analyses were conducted for the intersections noted in Section II, in the vicinity of the
proposed QRTP, using the Synchro Professional Software, version 8.0 according to the methods
described in the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual, published by the Transportation Research
Board. Analyses were conducted for the 2013 Existing, 2023 No‐Build, and 2023 Build
Conditions. The analyses indicate that each of the intersections studied presently operate at
Levels of Service (LOS) C or better during both the AM and PM peak periods for both the
existing and No‐Build conditions. The analyses show that the intersections of Kennedy Drive at
the I‐395 SB Exit ramp / Site Drive and Kennedy Road at Route 44 will require improvements to
operate at an LOS D or better once the QRTP is fully occupied. The anticipated improvements
for these locations are as follows:
Kennedy Drive at I‐395 SB Exit Ramp / Site Drive
 Widen Kennedy Drive to provide an exclusive NB left turn lane
Quinebaug Regional Tech Park | Traffic Impact Study
It is not anticipated that these improvements are needed immediately but will become
necessary as the QRTP is developed. The improvements will be necessary after the 48,000
square foot YMCA and 150,000 square feet of office/industrial use are developed. The YMCA
would be first development on the site.
With the completion of the proposed roadway improvement, the roadway network in the
vicinity of the proposed Quinebaug Regional Tech Park will safely accommodate the anticipated
traffic generated by the full development.
Quinebaug Regional Tech Park | Traffic Impact Study
The purpose of this study is to evaluate the traffic impact of the proposed Quinebaug Regional
Tech Park (QRTP) located on 267± acres along the west side of Kennedy Drive in the Town of
Putnam. The site is currently owned by the Town of Putnam. Access to the site will be via a
new roadway to be constructed intersecting the west side of Kennedy Drive opposite the I‐395
SB Exit Ramp. When completed it is anticipated that the QRTP will consist of approximately 20
buildings totaling 1,400,000 square feet of light industrial/ office use and a 48,000 square foot
regional YMCA facility. It is intended that this report be responsive to the concerns of the Town
of Putnam and the State of Connecticut Department of Economic and Community Development
with regard to the impact of the proposed development on the surrounding roadways.

Making manual turning movement counts at 7 intersections in the vicinity of the site.

Average Weekday Trip Generation is the total traffic generation of a development on a typical
Peak Hourly Generation is traffic generation that may be anticipated during the highest volume

depending on the type of facility being proposed.

Currently access to the site is via a driveway intersecting the west side of Kennedy Drive
approximately 675 feet to the north of the I‐395 SB Off Ramp. The current drive currently
crosses Quinebaug River via a single lane bridge. Secondary access is provided from the west
via Town Farm Road, a rural residential street. (See Exhibit 1)
The site is served regionally by I‐395 and Route 44. I‐395 is a limited access interstate highway
oriented in the north‐south direction. It connects Putnam with the City of Norwich to the south
and Worcester, MA to the north. Interchange 95 along I‐395 provides full access to the
interstate from Kennedy Drive. Route 44 is a principal arterial roadway traveling in the east‐
west direction. Route 44 connects Putnam with the towns of Ashford and Pomfret to the west
and towns of East Putnam and Chepachet, RI to the east. Route 44 intersects Kennedy Drive at
a signalized intersection approximately 1.25 miles north of the site.
In the vicinity of the site, Kennedy Drive is a two lane roadway oriented in the north‐south
direction. Kennedy Drive is classified as a collector in the Town of Putnam. It begins in the

Based on a review of ATR counts conducted by CDOT, there has been a decrease in traffic
volumes in the vicinity of the site since 2006. This reduction in traffic is believed to be caused
by the current economic slow‐down the country has been experiencing and as the economy
improves, we believe the traffic volumes on the adjacent roadways will increase. To account
for this growth, an annual background growth rate of 0.5 percent per year was used to grow
the Existing 2013 volumes. The growth rate was applied to the Existing 2013 traffic volumes to
determine the projected Year 2023 traffic volumes, which is defined as the design year traffic
without the proposed development, or No‐Build conditions. Background traffic volumes are
summarized in a traffic flow diagram presented in Exhibit 3.
The impact of the proposed development is determined by calculating the number of trips that
are expected to be generated by the development and subsequently assigning the trips to the
surrounding roadway network. The trip generation volumes represent the number of trips
expected to be added to the roadway during the peak hours of the adjacent street. The
Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) publication Trip Generation, 8th edition, 2008,
contains trip generation information for various types of Land Uses, including several for office
/ industrial parks and athletic club / recreational uses. Land Use 130, “Industrial Park”,
correlates well with the proposed Quinebaug Regional Tech Park development and Land Use
495 “Community Center” is the best land use to match with the proposed YMCA. The new trips
anticipated to be added to the roadway network by the proposed 1,448,000 square foot QRTP

The total new site generated traffic anticipated is 865 vehicle trips during the weekday morning
peak hour and 1190 vehicle trips during the weekday afternoon peak hour. 693 vehicles will
enter and 171 vehicles will exit the development during the morning peak hour and 261
vehicles will enter and 929 vehicles will exit the facility during the afternoon peak hour.
The direction from which vehicles are expected to arrive and depart the site is important in
determining the impact that the generated traffic will have on the roadway system. The arrival
and departure distribution was determined by the existing volumes on the roadway network. It
is assumed that all traffic will access the QRTP via Kennedy Drive and that the access from River
Road/Town Farm Road will be restricted to emergency vehicle access only. The peak hour trip
distribution percentages and site generated traffic volumes are presented in Exhibits 4 and 5,

Exhibits 7 and 8 present the results of the capacity analyses for the Existing and 2023 No‐Build
volumes. These exhibits indicates that each of the intersections studied presently operate at
Levels of Service (LOS) C or better during both the AM and PM peak periods for both the
existing and No‐Build conditions. Exhibit 9 presents the results of the capacity analyses for the
2023 Build Volumes. This exhibit indicates that the intersection of Kennedy Drive at the I‐395
SB Exit ramp / Site Drive and the intersection of Kennedy Road at Route 44 will require
improvements to operate at an LOS D or better once the QRTP is fully occupied. The
anticipated improvements for these locations are as follows:
Kennedy Drive at I‐395 SB Exit Ramp / Site Drive
 Widen Kennedy Road to provide an exclusive NB left turn lane
The exclusive left turn lane will need to be approximately 300 feet long in order to provide
sufficient storage for left turning vehicles. There is sufficient right‐of‐way to accommodate
widening of the existing road to add this 12 foot wide left turn lane.
Exhibit 10 presents the results of the capacity analyses for the 2023 Build volumes with the
proposed improvements. These exhibits indicates that the two intersections needing
improvements will operate at an LOS D or better during both the AM and PM peak periods once
It is anticipated that the QRTP can start development without implementing the proposed
improvements. The need for the improvements is not anticipated until the QRTP consists of
the 48,000 square foot YMCA, and exceeds 150,000 square feet of office/industrial use.

Capacity analyses were conducted for the Existing, 2023 No‐Build and 2023 Build conditions for
the intersections surrounding the site. The results are presented in Exhibit 7, 8 and 9. Based on
these analyses, all of the intersections of Kennedy Drive at the I‐395 SB Exit ramp / Site Drive
and Kennedy Drive at Route 44 will require improvements to operate at an LOS D or better
once the QRTP is fully occupied. The results of the capacity analyses for the 2023 Build volumes
with the proposed improvements are presented in Exhibit 10.
Based on the findings of this report it is the professional opinion of Alfred Benesch & Company
that once the proposed roadway improvements are completed, the roadway network in the
vicinity of the proposed Quinebaug Regional Tech Park will safely accommodate the anticipated
traffic generated by the full development.
